Context

A close friend who happens to be a Taylor Swift fan is asking for our help in order to understand the evolution of the singer in terms of her lyrics and song messages. We will gather information on each of her songs, the release date and the album to which each song pertains and carry out computational analysis to tell our story.

Opening hypothesis: With extremely limited previous knowledge about Taylor´s songs, we will be taking advantage of a range of text mining tools in order to understand better the song topics of such a worldwide successful artist. As an opening theory, we will stick to the conjecture that she plays with the theme of love in most of her songs (this could apply to many singers nowadays). Even though not being a declared fan (a Swiftie), one cannot escape from listening to many of her songs in TV adds, the radio, youtube playlists etc. Since her popularity and achievements are so outstanding, we could guess that her music suits a wide majority of the audience (mainly pop music). However, let´s begin with our project and study these views deeper!

Our departure point will be to load the required libraries for the analysis.

Frequency analysis

We will perform some simple statistical analysis to begin with. It might be interesting to calculate the frequency of appearance of each word in the whole course of Taylor´s music trajectory and plot the results. In literary studies, analyzing word frequency can provide insights into an author’s writing style, as well as the historical and cultural context in which the work was written. In this case, these techniques will be applied to Taylor´s songs:

taylor_words <- lyrics %>% 
  #group dataframe by words (many are repeated over and over in different albums/songs)
  group_by(word) %>% 
  #count the number of appearances
  count() %>% 
  #sort in a descending order
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  ungroup()

We do find some other interesting words like “mad”, “forever”, “hate” or “wrong”, which means that there is some degree of anger or pain expressed in her songs.

Sentiment analysis

Now we will analyse her lyrics by resorting to a sentiment analysis. We will first take advantage of afinn which is based on a regression analysis on sentiment and assigns a value from [-3,3] to each word. A sentiment analysis enables us to automatically identify and extract subjective information from text data. It involves analyzing the lyrics to determine the overall sentiment or attitude of the artist, whether positive, negative, or neutral. We will group by song in order to perform a net sentiment (sum of all positive and negative values) analysis and plot our results.

afinn <- lyrics %>% 
  #join with afinn words list
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>% 
  #group by song in chronological order
  group_by(track_title,year) %>% 
  #summarise the net value
  summarise(net_sentiment = sum(value)) %>% 
  #sort by time
  arrange(year) %>% 
  ungroup()

Recall we have been using the afinn method up to now, but we will take advantage now of bing to explore a similar plot by year. Bing contains 2 levels for each word, “positive” and “negative”.

bing <- lyrics %>% 
  #join with list of words in bing
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>% 
  #group by the sentiment and year and count the frequency
  group_by(year,sentiment) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  #set to wider format by reshaping the data
  pivot_wider(names_from = sentiment,
              values_from = n) %>% 
  #calculate net value of the count
  mutate(net_sentiment = positive-negative)

Term frequency and IDF

Now we will upgrade the word frequency analysis into a more scientific method. We have already counted the words appearing the most in each of the albums, but one would like a measure of distinctiveness. A word is distinctive of a document if its appearance in such a file is more often relative to the rest of the documents. We will analyse these metrics by album and plot the results to find useful patterns. A high IDF score for a particular term indicates that the term is relatively rare or unique within the corpus (takes place in just a few songs or albums), and is therefore more important. The TF-IDF score for a term within a document is calculated by multiplying the term frequency by the inverse document frequency.

In order to call the function bind_tf_i, we will first have to compute the three corresponding columns which enter as arguments:

lyrics_idf <- lyrics %>% 
  #We group by album and word
  group_by(album,word) %>% 
  #Count how many observations
  count() %>%
  #Ungroup at the end
  ungroup()

Now we can enter this information into the tf_idf function and obtain the top 10 records:

lyrics_idf_top <- lyrics_idf %>%
  #calculate the corresponding metrics
  bind_tf_idf(word,album,n) %>% 
  #arrange from highest to lowest tf_idf
  arrange(album,desc(tf_idf)) %>%
  #group by each album
  group_by(album) %>% 
  #obtain top records
  slice(1:10)
#vizualise results
lyrics_idf_top %>% 
  head()
## # A tibble: 6 × 6
## # Groups:   album [1]
##   album word           n      tf   idf tf_idf
##   <chr> <chr>      <int>   <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 1989  ey            72 0.0375  1.79  0.0672
## 2 1989  woods         38 0.0198  1.79  0.0355
## 3 1989  shake         78 0.0406  0.693 0.0282
## 4 1989  wonderland    21 0.0109  1.79  0.0196
## 5 1989  york          27 0.0141  1.10  0.0155
## 6 1989  blood         16 0.00834 1.79  0.0149

The tf_idf compensates for the amount of documents (in this case, albums) holding the term inside it while at the same time it increases in relation to the number of times such a document contains the specific term. This means that, for a word to be distinctive of a document, it must be in relation to the whole collection of albums and not just to a specific album/song. This differs from the analysis on word frequency we performed at the beginning of the project.

lyrics_idf_top %>% 
  #Enter information into ggplot()
  ggplot()+
  #Select tf_idf and word as aesthetics with a reordering parameter
  aes(tf_idf, reorder_within(word,tf_idf,album),fill = album) +
  #Set stat to identity 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
  #facet by album
  facet_wrap(~album, scales = "free")+
  labs(y = "Word")+
  #Dark theme with more readable facet titles
  theme_dark()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 6),
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none",
        strip.text = element_text(color = "white",size = 12))+
  #Apply scaling to make it more readable for user
  scale_y_reordered()

One finds that words that are distinctive of each album are terms like “grow”, “getaway”,“trouble” or “rains”. We have now learnt that “trouble”, which we saw was repeated several times at the sentiment analysis, it pertains to album “Red” and it is actually distinctive of this album. This means that it is overused inside this album with respect to other albums. However, we do find many words which happen to have a high tf_idf but without any specific meaning such as “ho”, “la” or “mm”.

Let´s filter these words and repeat the analysis by generating our proper stopwords:

#Generat personalized stopwords
our_stopwords <- c("ey","aah","la","mm","ooh","ha","na","ho")
lyrics_idf <- lyrics_idf %>% 
  #anti join with our stopwords
  anti_join(data.frame(word = our_stopwords))
## Joining, by = "word"
lyrics_idf_top <- lyrics_idf %>% 
  #compute idf metrics again
  bind_tf_idf(word,album,n) %>% 
  #arrange in descending order
  arrange(album,desc(tf_idf)) %>% 
  group_by(album) %>% 
  #fins top 10 records
  slice(1:10)

Notice that we don´t find anymore the cloud of words which we described in our personalized stop words. Word “fearless” is distinctive of the album “fearless” (makes sense) and words like “careful”, “enchanted” or “sparks” are distincttive of album “Speak now”, which means that this must be an album centered in speaking about maybe some confusing or frustrating love experience and someone that “messed” with her -> gives rise to the title of this album, “Speak now” and tell the world.

Zipf’s law

It is a good chance to explore Zipf´s law inside Taylor Swift´s albums. This law states that the frequency of word appearance will be inversely proportional to its rank, so we shall find a clear negative trend when analyzing this (logarithmic) relation:

rank <- lyrics_idf %>% 
  #compute idf metrics
  bind_tf_idf(word,album,n) %>% 
  #arrange in descending order
  arrange(desc(tf)) %>% 
  #group by album
  group_by(album) %>% 
  #create column accounting for rank
  mutate(rank = row_number()) %>% 
  ungroup()
rank

Now we can plot these results by changing the scales into a logarithmic one:

rank %>% 
  ggplot(aes(rank, tf, color = album)) +

  geom_line(size = 1.2, alpha = 0.8, show.legend = FALSE) + 
  #change scales to logarithmic
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10()+
  #set a dark theme
  theme_dark()+
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank())+
  labs(title = "Zipf´s law")+
  #annotations to add comprehension for the user
  annotate("text", label = "Clear negative relationship \n in all albums",
           x = 80, y = 0.015, color = "white", size = 6)

N-grams and word context

Up to now, we have been dealing with individual words or tokens inside Taylor Swift songs, but this limits our analysis and we might lose some context since one might be interested in chunks of words arranged together or appearing close to each other in a given context. N-grams are a technique used in natural language processing and computational linguistics to represent text as a sequence of contiguous words. An n-gram is a contiguous sequence of n items from a given sample of text, where an item can be a word, a character, or a symbol.

Let´s read from scratch our lyric data:

Improve tf_idf with bigrams

Incorporating bigrams into our TF-IDF analysis can help us extract more relevant information from the text data, and gain a deeper understanding of the underlying patterns and structures in the lyrics. Recall we had performed word frequencies and tf_idf taks on individual terms, but we will extend this analysis to our already built bigrams to improve our project:

bigrams_idf <- bigrams_sep %>% 
  #merge together both columns into a single bigram
  unite(bigram, word1,word2, sep = " ") %>% 
  #group by album and bigram and count frequencies

  count() %>% 
  #Our function for tf_idf analysis is called
  bind_tf_idf(bigram,album,n) %>% 
  #arrange in descending order
  arrange(desc(tf_idf))

Network of bigrams

This is a graphical representation of the co-occurrence relationships between pairs of words in a text corpus. In a bigram network, each word in the corpus is represented as a node, and each pair of adjacent words is represented as an edge connecting the two corresponding nodes. We will also explore the phi coefficient which tells us the correlation between two words appearing together inside the same context (here we will perform this by album groups) relative to the number of appearances of these words by themselves.

graph <- bigrams_sep %>%

We can already see some words appearing together such as “true” and “love” or “body” and “heart”, but we might be more interested in the context than in words that are necessarily next to each other.

What are the most frequent words accompanying the word “love”? This is one of the most frequent words found at word frequency counts we analyzed at earlier stages. To do this, we will explore both words coming after and before the word “love”, or bigrams containing such a term.

While our previous word frequency analysis looked at individual words and their frequency of use, bigram analysis incorporates the co-occurrence of pairs of words and their frequency of use together.

By analyzing the frequency of bigrams (in combination with word frequency), we can gain insights into the ways in which words are used in combination with each other, and identify common word combinations or phrases that are used frequently within a text. This can help us better understand the overall meaning and structure of Taylor´s songs, as well as the singer’s style and tone.

Word correlation and phi coefficient

We will first count the number of times two words appear under the same context (recall we have grouped by songs and we have more than 90 songs in total). To do this, we resort to the function pairwise_count() which counts the number of times each pair of items appear together within a group defined by “feature.” Under this context, the features are our song titles:

lyrics %>% 
  #tokenize 
  unnest_tokens(word,lyric) %>% 
  #remove stopwords
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% 
  #calculate pairwise count with grouping by song
  pairwise_count(word,track_title, sort = TRUE)
## Joining, by = "word"
## # A tibble: 230,328 × 3
##    item1 item2     n
##    <chr> <chr> <dbl>
##  1 love  time     25
##  2 time  love     25
##  3 time  night    22
##  4 night time     22
##  5 time  eyes     16
##  6 love  eyes     16
##  7 eyes  time     16
##  8 eyes  love     16
##  9 mind  love     16
## 10 love  mind     16
## # … with 230,318 more rows

The most common word appearences under the same context (song) are “time” with “love”, “time” with “night” and the term “eyes” with many other of the previous terms. This means that these terms are commonly linked together under the same context such that Taylor might devote a lot of importance to time consuming, past love and maybe a loneliness feeling in which she feels more comfortable and at peace at night.

A more important measure is the phi coefficient, which excludes terms that appear frequently under all contexts. This is because it compares the number of times that these words appear together with the number of times these words appear by themselves:

cor <- lyrics %>% 
  #tokenize
  unnest_tokens(word,lyric) %>% 
  #filter stopwords on words
  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word) %>% 
  #compute correlations by song
  pairwise_cor(word,track_title, sort = TRUE)
head(cor)

##   item1     item2   correlation

## 2 tendency  georgia           1
## 3 stuck     georgia           1
## 4 backroads georgia           1
## 5 tim       georgia           1
## 6 mcgraw    georgia           1

Let´s enter this information in ggplot() and filter for the most common appearances of the word love. Recall we are computing the correlation coefficient, so this will account for the number of times that the term “love” appears with other words under the same context more often than it appears by itself.

cor %>% 
  #filter 
  filter(item1 == "love" | item2 == "love") %>% 
  #sort in descending order
  arrange(desc(correlation)) %>% 
  #merge columns together and filter for top 15 results
  unite(context, item1, item2, sep = " ") %>% 
  slice(1:15) %>% 
   ggplot()+
  #reorder by correlation coefficient
  aes(correlation, reorder(context,correlation))+
  #set bar colors
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black", fill = "blue")+
  theme_dark()+
  labs(y = " ", title = "Correlations with word love")+
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank())+
  #include text labeling in white to contrast
  geom_text(aes(label = context), hjust = 1.5, color = "white")

There we go, these are the most correlated terms with the word “love” according to our phi coefficient. By far, the most frequent instances take place when love appears in the same context as “deep” followed by “losing” and “boys”. We are confirming that love for Taylor is usually linked to deep emotions for boys (so we can discard other forms of love such as family or friends) and, once again, we notice some correlation with words like “losing” or “miss” to stress this melancholic feeling of regret present in many of her songs.

Sparcity and Time evolution

Up to now, we have been working with lyrics on a tidy format such that we operated one token per row in our data frame. As a closing section to our project, let´s plot a time evolution of the most relevant words for Taylor and mutate the data into DTM in order to explore the concept of Sparcity. Sparsity in text mining refers to the phenomenon where a large proportion of the terms in a document or corpus occur very infrequently or not at all. In other words, the majority of the terms have a frequency of zero or close to zero.

First, we will use our original lyrics data and unnest tokens just as we did at earlier stages of the study. We generate a new column accounting for the percentage of times a term is used in relation to the whole frequency of terms by year. This is done to standardize since one could find years in which Taylor had launched more than 10 songs and others in which she just introduced a new single. Whatever the case, we will group by year and plot the evolution of the usage of words “love”, “time” and “baby”:

lyrics %>% 
  #Split all the tokens and care for punctuation
  unnest_tokens(word,lyric, drop = TRUE,
                "strip_punct" = TRUE) %>% 
  #We select only the columns we are interested in 
  select(album,track_title,year,word) %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% 
  count(year,word) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  #Generate new columns for total words and percentage usage
  mutate(total = sum(n), perc = n/total) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  #we filter by our terms vector
  filter(word %in% c("love", "time", "baby")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, perc, color = word)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(group = 1) +
  #facet the result by word
  facet_wrap(~ word, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(Title = "Temporal Frequency of Taylor´s Terms")+
  theme_dark()+
  #remove grid lines
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=unique(lyrics$year))

The shape of these functions is very similar, which could mean a high correlation between the usage of these words. However, the word “time” seems to be a “lead variable” since both its peak and trough happen before the terms “love” and “baby”. The frequency of these words skyrocket between 2014 and 2017. This could match with the fact that, in early 2015, Taylor Swift began dating Scottish DJ and music producer Calvin Harris. The couple had a highly publicized relationship, with many of their outings and social media posts making headlines, and they even collaborated on the song “This Is What You Came For” together.

Finally, we can explore Sparcity by year to understand better our previous plot:

lyrics %>% 
  #Split all the tokens and care for punctuation

  cast_dtm(year, word, n)

One spots a sparsity of 71% on 6 documents (one for each year of data we own) and just 1957 terms. This means that 71% of the elements in the matrix are 0, which means that, in fact, Taylor´s speech along time is not changing much and she is resorting to the same terms in many of her songs. After all, she is a 12 Grammy Award winner and has been, for more than a decade, one of the top selling artists worldwide, so we can understand her style is so stagnant along time (if this is what it works for her)!

Final Remarks

In this project, we have dealt with a text mining process to uncover and explain Taylor Swift´s writing style and analyse the evolution and trends of word frequencies, distinctiveness, Sparsity etc. However, notice we are just operating with text, but music has other factors which makes Taylor a very successful artist such as her voice, her music knowledge, the timing of song releases, the language of her songs etc. A future research topic which could contribute to our findings and enhance the proposed project could be to combine text mining techniques with other types of structured data such as floats or dates in order to search for potentially interesting relationships (e.g. Is the evolution of Taylor´s sentiment correlated with the amount of records sold? Is there a particular context or topic preferred by the audience? What songs have lasted for longer on the top 100 billboard and how can we account for this by resorting to text mining techniques? etc.)

Our word frequencies and counts revealed that terms such as “feel,” “kiss,” “home,” or “girl” follow were consistent with our previous analysis that Taylor Swift’s entire discography appears to be intended to express emotions related to girls, romance, and the feeling of being comfortable or at home. However, some other notable words such as “mad,” “forever,” “hate,” or “wrong” also appear, indicating that her songs also convey some degree of exasperation or pain.

However, an improved version of this technique was implied when dealing with tf_idf such that we observed how the word “fearless” was specific to the album with the same name, which was not that surprising. Additionally, words such as “careful”, “enchanted,” and “sparks” are unique to the album “Speak Now”. One can suggest that the album focuses on expressing a potentially perplexing or frustrating love experience, likely involving someone who has caused her some emotional turmoil. This theme is reflected in the album’s title, “Speak Now,” which invites her to speak her truth and share her story with the world. This was one of her top selling albums of all time.

When resorting to bigrams and phi correlation techniques, we established that the words most strongly correlated with “love” are “deep,” “losing,” and “boys.” The most frequent instances of these words occur in contexts where love is described as deep, followed by references to “losing” and “boys”. This suggests that, for Taylor Swift, love is typically associated with intense emotions towards boys, rather than other forms of love such as family or friends. Once again, according to the Phi Coefficient, these are linked to the notion of “losing” or “miss,” emphasizing the sorrowful feeling of regret that is often available in her songs.
